
[1]broach

   BROACH, n.

   1. A spit, and in some parts of the English dominions, an awl, and a
   bodkin.

   2. A musical instrument played by turning a handle.

   3. A clasp or small utensil to fasten a vest. [See Brooch.]

   4. A start of the head of a young stag.

                                BROACH, v.t.

   1. To spit; to pierce as with a spit.

   2. To tap; to pierce, as a cask, in order to draw the liquor; hence, to
   let out.

   3. To open, as a store. [Unusual.]

   4. To utter; to give out; to publish first; to make public what was
   before unknown; as, to broach an opinion.

   To broach to, in navigation, to incline suddenly to windward, so as to
   lay the sails aback and expose the vessel to the danger of oversetting.
